equation_narrative.headline: Glycine emerges from charged context via late-layer flexibility encoding
equation_narrative.story: Position 35 sits in a charged, surface-exposed environment flanked by acidic residues (IQDKE[G]IPPDQ). Early layers (L1-17) assemble a representation consistent with polar and small residues (S, N, T dominate the logit lens at 12-23%), reflecting the local chemistry and structural openness. The representation shifts decisively at L22 when glycine-specific features activate, jumping from 13.6% to 34.9%. Decision layers (L24-33) amplify this signal through MLP neurons encoding backbone flexibility and turn propensity, with glycine reaching 91.2% by L33. The model correctly identifies that this position requires maximal conformational freedom in a tight turn between charged residues.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather context from 3 structural contacts and 29 co-evolving positions. Early attention (L1-9) reads the charged local sequence (K33, D34, E36), producing a representation consistent with polar residues—serine peaks at 22.6% at L0, reflecting the hydrophilic environment. Mid-layers (L9-18) show frequent lead changes between small polar residues (S, N, T) and small hydrophobics (A, L), indicating the model is encoding both the surface exposure and the need for a compact residue. By L17-23, glycine begins to emerge (13.6% at L17) as features encoding turn propensity and backbone flexibility activate. The logit lens trajectory through this phase reflects the assembly of a 'small, flexible, surface-compatible' representation rather than prediction.
perception_phase.context_character: Surface-exposed position in a charged environment (flanked by D34, K33, E36) requiring a small, flexible residue. The structural contacts are sparse (only 3), consistent with a turn or loop region. Co-evolutionary signal is strong (29 positions), suggesting functional importance of backbone flexibility at this site.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 3 residues within 8Å (sparse contact pattern typical of turns/loops)
Co-evolutionary coupling: 29 positions (strong functional constraint on backbone flexibility)
Local sequence: charged residues at ±1,±2 positions (D34, K33, E36, D39) create polar environment
L18 attention features: F18:4071 (19.3 proj) and F18:1860 (18.4 proj) encode turn/loop context
L19 velocity: +2.36 total_delta driven by attention (+2.01) reading structural openness

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L22-23 when glycine jumps from 13.6% to 38.2%, driven by MLP neurons encoding backbone flexibility (N21:1490 projects 0.698 toward G, N21:896 projects 0.467). Layers 24-30 show competition between glycine and small polar alternatives (N peaks at 12.2% at L29, E reaches 12.0% at L30), but glycine-specific prediction channels dominate. The final surge occurs at L31-33: MLP neurons N31:2392 (0.817 proj) and N31:5068 (0.728 proj) strongly favor glycine, while SAE features F33:88 (86.4 proj) and F33:9022 (78.9 proj) encode glycine-specific turn propensity. Glycine reaches 91.2% by L33.
decision_phase.transition: At L22-23, the representation shifts from 'small and flexible' to 'specifically glycine.' L22 MLP (+1.95 total_delta) activates turn-encoding neurons, causing glycine to jump from 13.6% to 34.9%. L23 shows brief hesitation (-2.07 total_delta) as the model weighs polar alternatives, but L24 onward commits to glycine as the only residue providing sufficient backbone freedom for this tight turn.

candidates.narrative: Glycine emerges decisively at L22 (jumping from 13.6% to 34.9%) and dominates through the decision phase. Key support comes from flexibility-encoding MLP neurons: N21:1490 (0.698 proj), N29:878 (0.507 proj), N30:3816 (0.652 proj), and N31:2392 (0.817 proj). Late-layer SAE features encode glycine-specific turn propensity: F33:88 (86.4 proj, MLP source) and F33:9022 (78.9 proj, MLP source). The final probability of 91.2% reflects strong consensus that this position requires maximal backbone flexibility.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L17 (13.6%), decisive at L22 (34.9%), dominant by L29 (49.2%), final 91.2%
key_evidence: N21:1490 (0.698 proj toward G) — flexibility-encoding neuron
N31:2392 (0.817 proj toward G) — strongest late-layer writer
F33:88 (86.4 proj, MLP) — glycine-specific turn channel
F33:9022 (78.9 proj, MLP) — backbone flexibility feature

candidates.narrative: Serine leads the logit lens at L0 (22.6%), reflecting the representation's initial encoding of the polar, surface-exposed context. This is NOT a prediction—it indicates that the early representation correlates with small polar residues compatible with charged neighbors. Serine remains prominent through L17 (12.2%) as the model assembles turn-compatible features, but loses ground once glycine-specific flexibility encoding activates at L22. Final probability is only 1.8%.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L0 (22.6%), declines through perception phase, eliminated by L29 (4.0%)
key_evidence: L0 dominance reflects polar context encoding, not prediction
Competes with N and T through L23 as model encodes 'small polar' character
Lacks backbone flexibility features needed for tight turn

candidates.narrative: Asparagine represents the model's consideration of polar alternatives to glycine. It peaks at L14 (15.4%) and maintains 11-12% through L23-29 as the model weighs whether a polar sidechain could satisfy both the charged environment and flexibility requirements. However, decision-phase neurons favor glycine's unique backbone freedom: N peaks at 12.2% at L29 but drops to 1.6% by L33 as glycine-specific channels dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L14 (15.4%), sustained through L29 (12.2%), eliminated by L33 (1.6%)
key_evidence: Represents 'small polar with sidechain' alternative to glycine
Lacks support from flexibility-encoding neurons in L24-33
Eliminated by glycine-specific features at L30-33

candidates.narrative: Aspartate emerges late (peaks at 7.8% at L29) as the model briefly considers whether a charged residue could satisfy the local electrostatic environment. This reflects reading of the charged neighbors (K33, D34, E36), but aspartate's larger sidechain and reduced backbone flexibility make it incompatible with the turn geometry. Final probability is 2.95%, making it the distant runner-up.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L23 (2.4%), peaks at L29 (7.8%), final 2.95%
key_evidence: Lacks flexibility features needed for tight turn
Sidechain bulk incompatible with structural constraints

turning_points.description: The representation transitions from 'small polar' to 'specifically glycine.' At L17, glycine first leads the logit lens (13.6%), overtaking serine. L19 shows +2.36 velocity (attention-driven) as structural openness features activate. L22 is decisive: MLP neurons encoding turn propensity fire (+1.95 total_delta from N22:1414, N22:1689), causing glycine to jump from 13.6% to 34.9%. This marks the shift from perception (assembling turn context) to decision (committing to glycine as the only residue with sufficient backbone freedom).

Final commitment phase. L29-31 show strong MLP support for glycine: N29:878 (0.507 proj), N30:3816 (0.652 proj), N31:2392 (0.817 proj) all favor glycine over polar alternatives. L31 attention erases competing candidates (-4.58 attn_delta) via heads reading co-evolutionary constraints. L33 delivers the final surge: MLP neurons N33:88 and N33:9022 (via SAE features F33:88 at 86.4 proj and F33:9022 at 78.9 proj) encode glycine-specific turn propensity, pushing probability from 73.4% to 91.2%.

deep_dives.label: Early polar context (L1-9)
deep_dives.caption: L1 and L9 features encode the charged local environment. These features reflect what's around position 35 (K33, D34, E36), producing a representation consistent with polar residues. This is context assembly, not prediction.

deep_dives.label: Turn encoding emerges (L18)
deep_dives.caption: L18 attention features (F18:4071 at 19.3 proj, F18:1860 at 18.4 proj) encode turn/loop structural context. The sparse structural contacts (only 3) and charged neighbors create a representation consistent with backbone flexibility requirements.

deep_dives.label: Glycine commitment (L21-23 MLPs)
deep_dives.caption: L21-22 MLPs activate flexibility-encoding neurons (N21:1490 projects 0.698 toward G, N22:1414 projects 0.316). L22 shows +1.95 total_delta, causing glycine to jump from 13.6% to 34.9%. L23 hesitates (-2.07 delta) before final commitment.

deep_dives.label: Glycine prediction channels (L30-33)
deep_dives.caption: Late-layer MLP neurons strongly favor glycine: N30:3816 (0.652 proj), N31:2392 (0.817 proj), N32:4002 (0.834 proj). These neurons encode turn propensity and backbone flexibility, the decisive evidence for glycine.

deep_dives.label: Final glycine features (L33)
deep_dives.caption: L33 SAE features encode glycine-specific turn propensity: F33:88 (86.4 proj, MLP source) and F33:9022 (78.9 proj, MLP source) are the strongest prediction channels. These features represent the model's final commitment to glycine as the only residue providing sufficient backbone freedom.

deep_dives.label: Co-evolutionary erasure (L31-32)
deep_dives.caption: L31-32 attention heads erase competing candidates by reading co-evolutionary constraints. L32 head 5 (-2.29 proj, 19.8% coevol attention) and head 18 (-2.24 proj, 16.0% coevol attention) suppress polar alternatives, enforcing glycine as the functionally constrained residue.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts glycine by assembling a representation of a surface-exposed, charged environment requiring maximal backbone flexibility. Early layers (L1-17) encode the polar context and sparse structural contacts, producing a 'small, flexible, surface-compatible' representation reflected in the logit lens as S, N, and T. The decisive shift occurs at L22 when flexibility-encoding MLP neurons activate, recognizing that only glycine provides sufficient conformational freedom for a tight turn between charged residues. Late layers (L29-33) amplify this through glycine-specific prediction channels (F33:88 at 86.4 proj, N31:2392 at 0.817 proj), reaching 91.2% confidence. The strongest evidence is the convergence of turn-propensity features and the elimination of all alternatives that would introduce sidechain bulk or reduce backbone flexibility.
